    "problemDescription": "Combined problem descriptions from all Cinema Platform services.\n\n# billboard-service\nCinema platforms need a centralized service to schedule showtimes across theaters,\ntrack seat availability in real time, enforce booking business rules, and coordinate\nwith catalog and payment services. Without a dedicated billboard service, scheduling\nlogic leaks into multiple apps, seat state becomes inconsistent, and integrations\nare brittle.\n\n# catalog-service\nCinema platforms need a single source of truth for movies, cinema locations,\ntheater screens, and seat layouts. Downstream services (billboard, ticket, payment)\nrequire fast, consistent catalog lookups — often via gRPC — while admins need\nrich CRUD with business-rule enforcement and audit-friendly soft deletes.\n\n# concession-service\nTheaters need a unified backend for concession inventory — snacks, beverages,\ncombos, and time-limited promotions — with low-latency reads for POS systems\nand integration with ticketing/loyalty microservices. Monolithic catalogs lack\nflexible pricing, promotion rules, and protocol choice (REST vs gRPC).\n\n# employee-service\nCinema chains need a dedicated service to track staff across departments (projection,\nconcessions, ticketing, security, etc.), manage shift schedules, and handle vacation\napprovals. Without a centralized employee service, HR data fragments across spreadsheets\nand ad-hoc tools, schedule conflicts go undetected, and authorization for workforce\nAPIs becomes inconsistent across the platform.\n\n# notification-service\nEach Cinema Platform microservice historically handled its own emails, SMS, and\nin-app alerts. That leads to inconsistent templates, scattered SMTP/Twilio credentials,\nduplicate deliveries on retried Kafka events, and poor operational visibility when\nnotifications fail.\n\n# payment-service\nCinema purchases span tickets, concessions, merchandise, subscriptions, and wallet\ntop-ups across multiple services. A dedicated payment service must orchestrate\nprovider integration (Stripe), enforce refund rules, emit events, and expose\nrole-appropriate APIs while keeping PCI-sensitive data off the platform database.\n\n# ticket-service\nCinema platforms need reliable ticket purchasing, seat reservations, and lifecycle\nmanagement while integrating with billboard showtimes and payment authorization.\nHigh concurrency requires atomic seat handling with authoritative validation.\n\n# user-service\nCinema platforms need centralized user management for registration, authentication,\nprofiles, and authorization across microservices. Legacy systems often lack secure\nsession management, MFA, and event-driven lifecycle notifications.\n\n# wallet-service\nCinema platforms need a centralized wallet service so customers can preload\ncredit, pay for tickets and concessions, and review transaction history.\nWithout a dedicated wallet bounded context, payment logic leaks into order\nand user services, balances become inconsistent, and financial audit trails\nare incomplete.",
